<p><b>Robert Strange McNamara</b> (born June 9, 1916, in <a href="/wiki/Oakland,_California" title="Oakland, California">Oakland</a>, <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> business executive and the eighth <a href="/wiki/United_States_Secretary_of_Defense" title="United States Secretary of Defense">United States Secretary of Defense</a>. McNamara served as Defense Secretary during the <a href="/wiki/Vietnam_War" title="Vietnam War">Vietnam War</a> from 1961 to 1968. After holding that position he served as President of the <a href="/wiki/World_Bank" title="World Bank">World Bank</a> from 1968 until 1981. McNamara was responsible for the institution of <a href="/wiki/Systems_analysis" title="Systems analysis">systems analysis</a> in public policy, which developed into the discipline known today as <a href="/wiki/Policy_analysis" title="Policy analysis">policy analysis</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
